MALAYSIA DAYBOOK: Sime Darby, AirAsia Post Quarterly Earnings

-- B y   B a r r y   P o r t e r
-- 
2011-02-23T21:25:41Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-23/malaysia-daybook-sime-darby-airasia-post-quarterly-earnings.html
Sime Darby Bhd. (SIME MK), the
world’s biggest palm oil producer, is expected to report second-
quarter earnings after 5 p.m. The 100-year-old company returned
to profit in its fiscal first quarter after two quarterly losses
caused by write-downs from project overruns. It made total
provisions of 2.1 billion ringgit in the year ended June 30.  WHAT ELSE TO WATCH:
* AirAsia Bhd. (AIRA MK), Southeast  Asia ’s biggest budget
carrier, is also expected to announce fourth-quarter earnings
after 5 p.m.
* APFT Bhd. will unveil its listing prospectus at 10 a.m. in
Kuala Lumpur.  MARKETS:
* Malaysia’s FTSE Bursa  Malaysia  KLCI Index fell 0.2 percent.
* The MSCI Asia Pacific Index dropped 0.6 percent.
* The  Dow Jones Industrial Average  lost 0.9 percent.
* Palm oil May-delivery futures fell 4.2 percent to 3,514
ringgit ($1,153) a metric ton.  EQUITY PREVIEW:
* Genting Bhd. (GENT MK): Asia’s third-biggest casino operator
by market value said fourth-quarter profit almost doubled to
465.4 million ringgit, boosted by contributions from its new
Singapore gambling resort and higher palm oil prices.
* Hong Leong Bank Bhd. (HLBK MK): The lender controlled by
billionaire Quek Leng Chan said second-quarter profit jumped 30
percent to 291.4 million ringgit as an economic rebound spurred
demand for loans.
* KNM Group Bhd. (KNMG MK): The oil and gas services provider
said fourth-quarter net income more than halved to 20.6 million
ringgit on lower sales.
* Kossan Rubber Industries Bhd. (KRI MK): The rubber glove-maker
said fourth-quarter net income rose 21 percent to 29.5 million
ringgit.
*  Kuala Lumpur  Kepong Bhd. (KLK MK): The palm oil producer said
first-quarter profit increased 26 percent to 304.2 million
ringgit after fetching more money for its edible oil.
* Lion Corp. (LION MK): The steel producer and builder said it
had a loss of 98.6 million ringgit in the second quarter ended
Dec. 31 compared with a profit of 26.8 million ringgit a year
earlier as sales dropped.
* Malaysian Bulk Carriers Bhd. (MBC MK): The vessel operator
said fourth-quarter profit dropped 23 percent from a year
earlier to 67.7 million ringgit.
* Dayang Enterprise Holdings Bhd. (DEHB MK): The oil and gas
services provider said fourth-quarter profit almost tripled from
a year earlier to 17.9 million ringgit as sales surged.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Barry Porter in Kuala Lumpur at 
